{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}} '''Pharmaceutics''' is the discipline of [[pharmacy]] that deals with the process of turning a [[new chemical entity]] (NCE) or old drugs into a medication to be used safely and effectively by patients. It is also called the science of dosage form design. There are many chemicals with [[pharmacology|pharmacological]] properties, but need special measures to help them achieve therapeutically relevant amounts at their sites of action. Pharmaceutics helps relate the formulation of drugs to their delivery and disposition in the body.<ref name="washington1">{{cite web|url=http://sop.washington.edu/pharmaceutics/about/what-is-pharmaceutics.html |title=What is Pharmaceutics? &amp;#124; Pharmaceutics |publisher=Sop.washington.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-08-26}}</ref> Pharmaceutics deals with the formulation of a pure drug substance into a [[dosage form]]. Branches of pharmaceutics include: *[[Pharmaceutical formulation]] * *[[Pharmaceutical manufacturing]] *Dispensing pharmacy *Pharmaceutical technology *Physical pharmacy *Pharmaceutical jurisprudence Pure drug substances are usually white [[crystalline]] or [[amorphous]] powders. Historically before the advent of medicine as a science it was common for pharmacists to dispense drugs ''as is'', most drugs today are administered as parts of a dosage form. The clinical performance of drugs depends on their form of presentation to the patient.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rhodes|first1=edited by Gilbert S. Banker, Christopher T.|title=Modern Pharmaceutics, 1.|date=2002|publisher=Informa Healthcare|location=Hoboken|isbn=0824744691|edition=5th}}</ref>
==See also== *[[List of pharmaceutical companies]] *[[Pharmacognosy]] *[[Pharmaceutical company]] *[[Nicholas Culpeper]]&nbsp;– 17th-century English physician who translated and used "pharmocological texts"
